&c - then Mrs Swift
called - & she & Mrs Sargent
& self talked it over - &
concluded the cause of
change was the Brown
affair - not the suffrage
In P.M. Mrs Sargent
& self went to Palace Hotel
to call on Mrs Phebe H
Hearst - but found she
had gone to her county
seat - a new Spanish
style palace at Pleasanton
- then called on Hugh
Hume - Eve'g Post - who
insisted that Mrs Harper
told him Nat Com.
gave consent to his saying
[?] this new citizen [?]
assisted of the suffrage com?
entries.summaryText: Mrs Cooper and Mrs Swift visited Susan B. Anthony and discussed the Brown affair and its impact on the suffrage movement. Susan and Mrs. Sargent visited Mrs. Phebe H Hearst at the Palace Hotel and Hugh Hume at the Evening Post. They discussed Nat Com and a new citizen.

entries.fullText:
Sister Guelma's 78th birth
day - she passed on Nov 9/73
& her husband A.M. McLean
Jan. 18. 1896 - he remained
this side 29 years longer than she
This, too, is dear
Mrs Ellen C. Sargents 70th
birth day - Lunch at her
daughter Ella's - Montgomery's

A letter from nephew
Burt - Leavenworth Jul 27th -
he is well pleased there on
the paper - The Times -

Evening papers announce
death - this noon - of
Harriet Beecher Stowe [name underlined]
Hartford Ct - which
reaches only Isabella Beecher
Hooker of all of that
great Beecher Family -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony celebrated Sister Guelma's 78th birthday and Mrs. Ellen C. Sargent's 70th birthday. She received a letter from her nephew Burt and read about the death of Harriet Beecher Stowe.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Sargent - Mrs Blinn
Mr J [?],
self rode in only
carriage in the
4th of July procession
Mrs Murray
the one woman Anti
was also admitted to
the procession - in a
rear carriage - and
not as an invited guest -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony describes her participation in the 4th of July procession in San Francisco with Mrs. Sargent, Mrs. Blinn, Mr. J, and Mrs. Murray.

entries.fullText:
that is at Mrs Sargents -
Miss Hay out to
dinner - & in eve'g I
went with her to call
on Mr & Mrs Blinn -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends time at Mrs. Sargent's home and goes out to dinner with Miss Hay before visiting Mr. and Mrs. Blinn in the evening.

entries.fullText: Wea. MON. JULY 6, 1896 Ther
entries.summaryText: Entry with no additional information

entries.fullText:
San Francisco
at Mrs Sargents -
went to W. Knowles
grand avenue - first door
below Port - Dentist
in Plate work - had
my left side last tooth
taken out - at 9 A.M,
and at 4 P.M. - he had
the plate a new tooth
ready - so I ate my
dinner at six as usual
Mrs Sargent, Miss Hay & Mrs
Blinn went over to the Alameda
County meeting - Mrs Stocker Pres.
And Miss Mills - just
landed at 9 A.M. from
Eureka - Humbolt Co - went
to South Park meeting - Mrs
Osborn Pres -

Mrs Cooper, & Hattie -
telephoned to learn [?] Mrs C.
was not on the Central
Com -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits a dentist in San Francisco and has a tooth removed and replaced with a new one. She attends a meeting in Alameda County and another one in South Park. She also receives a phone call from Mrs. Cooper and Hattie.

geographicalLocations: 1201 Taylor St - San Fran. Cal - Mrs C. H. Rye - Oregon City
entries.fullText: This was thrown out - because of my accepting Mrs Cummings Congress on June 8.9.10 - so could not make two such long trips went again to Dentist this A.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's plans were cancelled due to a previous commitment and she went to the dentist.

entries.fullText:
Ida A. Harper
came this afternoon
& helped me write my
Examiner article
for Sundays issue -
she has wonderful
freedom of expression
the moment I give
the idea - the point -
she formulates it into
a good sentence -
while I should have
to higgle over it a
half hour - !!
entries.summaryText: Ida A. Harper helped Susan B. Anthony write an article for the Examiner.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw took this
engagement for me & so
saved me a second trip on
that long & lonely R.R.
Miss Hay asked that
Chairman of both the
Junta & Buckly [wings?] of
Mrs Duniway to invite - Mrs
Anthony to speak at their
ratifying meeting this evening
The Buckly man - Mr
Rothchilds tendered it
and Mrs Swift Mrs Harper
Miss Mills & Miss Hay -
went to Metropolitan Hall
with me - & I spoke
15 minutes to the so called
[unterrified ?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spoke for 15 minutes at a ratifying meeting in Metropolitan Hall, Oregon City, after Miss Shaw took her engagement and Miss Hay asked the Chairman of both the Junta and Buckly wings of Mrs Duniway to invite her.

entries.fullText:
After breakfast - Mrs
Harper & self went on
to Lemon Heights - Oakland
to Mr Havens - I took
Lunch & dinner - at lunch
were Mrs Cornwall Mrs
Mirssly & Mrs Bonnell
- All talked suffrage
so warmly - until I
broached money - that
always shuts people up -
Came home after
dinner alone -arriving
at 9.30 - all in bed - but
George not asleep - so was
quickly let in -
missed the Colored peoples
memorial meeting to Mrs
Stowe this evg - & felt
awfully sorry -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Lemon Heights in Oakland to visit Mr. Havens. She had lunch and dinner with Mrs. Cornwall, Mrs. Mirssly, and Mrs. Bonnell. They talked about suffrage until money was brought up. She missed the Colored peoples memorial meeting to Mrs. Stowe this evening and felt sorry.

entries.fullText:
Went to Dentist - Dr
Knowles at 9. A.M.
had right side clasp-
tooth filled - with
gold - as was the upper
wisdom tooth on that
side on last Thursday
& bid fair to carry
home a goodly quantity
of California gold
next November
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to the dentist, Dr. Knowles, to have a right side clasp-tooth filled with gold. She also had the upper wisdom tooth on that side filled with gold on the previous Thursday and joked about carrying home a goodly quantity of California gold next November.

entries.fullText:
Dentist Mr. Knowles in
at Port & Grand Streets -
at 8- A.M. again
Call on Mayor Sutro &
Taylor Rogers at City Hall
at 11.45 - found the
mayor perfectly innocent
of the fact that a suffrage
am't was to be voted
upon at next election
Took train for Wrights - near
Santa Cruz - at 2.45
to speak at Farmers
Congress in a camp - long
four miles from Station - was
met by a good scotch farmer
Mr Montgomery & taken
to his home - Mrs Woodhaven
came with him -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits the dentist and meets with Mayor Sutro and Taylor Rogers. She then takes a train to Wrights near Santa Cruz to speak at a Farmers Congress.

entries.fullText:
At Farmer Montgomery's
at 2.30 Oclock -
was taken some two
miles up the mountain
through the plum &
peach orchards to [the]
Camp Roach - & spoke
to 200 people mostly
women as usual -
- Mrs Miller
formerly of Lawrence
Kansas - all good
farmer women -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks to 200 people, mostly women, at Camp Roach.

entries.fullText:
Mr Montgomery - with
Mrs Miller took me
to the 11 A.M. train
to go to Pacific Grove -
stopped at Beach Hotel.
Santa Cruz to dinner
& reached the Grove
at 6. Mr E.P. Wilbur
Grand Ma Baker's son
met me - & took me to his
home - Aunt Mary & uncle
Eke - they call them -
on S.F. train that I took at
Watson were Mrs Sargent -
Mrs Goodrich, Miss Hay, Mrs Cooper
& daughter Harriet & Miss Shaw
& Mrs Blinn - all went with Mrs G.
to her niece Mrs Carvers except
Mrs C. & Hattie - niece Lucy E. met
with them also -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Pacific Grove and meets with various people on the way.

entries.fullText:
Pacific Grove - Chautauqua
Woman's Day - Mrs Sargent
Miss Hay - this is a Methodist
Camp - we had meetings
morning & afternoon - all handy
speaking & taking a collection
of a $100 - nearly -
In the evening Mrs
Shaw gave her "Fate
of Republics" to a
splendid audience -
& in her best mood !!
neither Mr nor Mrs
Wilbur went in evening -
both went in P.M. -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a Chautauqua Woman's Day event in Pacific Grove and listens to speeches and collections.

entries.fullText:
Left Pacific Grove at 6.40
A.M. - Mrs Coopers - Miss
Shaw Suzy & self - Shaw,
Suzy to take train for
Los Angeles at 5 P.M. for
a lecture tomorrow night
for the benefit of poor
Phoebe Couzins - it is
too sad that she has
come to such sad straits
- And I to speak
in Berkley at 8 -
at the Republican
Rally - dined &
slept at Mrs Willliam
Keiths the artist -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Pacific Grove to attend a Republican Rally in Berkley, while Suzy took a train to Los Angeles for a lecture.

entries.fullText:
Breakfasted & left
Mrs Keiths at 9 Oclock
Mrs Long met me at
Ferry & escorted me
to the
Socialist Labor Partys
Hall - where I spoke
to a hundred delegates
- they put strong
resolution in their
platform -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spoke to a hundred delegates at the Socialist Labor Party's Hall.

entries.fullText:
- $50 -
George R. Crow - Los Angeles -
- M Tho's Filken - manager
Took train Valencia Street
Station - at 827. to return
to Pacific Grove - the
girls met & took me to Mrs
Carners - made not
a free speech but a
hard one - every
sentence - & felt
like death about it -
all the more because
it was a hard lecture
But they all tried to
comfort me by saying it
was a good speech!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony returns to Pacific Grove, California, after giving a hard lecture in Los Angeles. She is comforted by the audience who thought it was a good speech.

entries.fullText:
At 6.40 Mrs Blinn
& Miss Hay left - &
at 11 - Mrs Goodrich took
Mrs Sargent & self to
Hotel Del Monte to
Lunch - then we
met Mrs Leland
Stanford -who had
just arrived - at
2 - Mrs J. & self took
train & reached
San Francisco at 7
Oclock evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony has lunch at Hotel Del Monte with Mrs. Goodrich and Mrs. Sargent. She meets Mrs. Leland Stanford who had just arrived. Later, she takes a train to San Francisco with Mrs. J.

entries.fullText: Went over to Oakland & Mrs Harper helped me out again with an article for the Examiner. Miss Molllie Connor Ed of Saturday night called & remained to Lunch & most of the afternoon. This should have been a Thursday page - [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Oakland and received help from Mrs. Harper with an article for the Examiner. Miss Molllie Connor visited and stayed for lunch and most of the afternoon.

entries.fullText: Worked all of this day till 5 P.M. - then rushed back in time for dinner - went to office after breakfast & Mrs Sweet copied article -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony worked all day until 5 P.M. and then rushed back in time for dinner. She went to the office after breakfast and Mrs. Sweet copied an article.

entries.fullText: Wrote all morning at 2 P.M. went riding in the Park with Dr & Ellen Montgomery - and George the driver of us all = at evening called at Mr Haskalls & talked over Populist [?] with Democrats at the St. Louis Con -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote in her journal on July 26, 1896 that she spent the morning writing, went riding in the park with Dr & Ellen Montgomery and George, and talked with Democrats about Populist at the St. Louis Con after visiting Mr. Haskalls in the evening.

entries.fullText: Mrs Sargent & self went to the Baptist Church [illegible mark here] to hear & see Mrs Naomi Anderson - a colored lecturer - Campaign Committee met this A.M. in 564 {E....?] Building at 10 O'clock - the money question - how to get it - is the burden of the hour -
entries.summaryText: On July 27, 1896, Susan B. Anthony wrote in her journal that she went to the Baptist Church in San Francisco to hear and see Mrs. Naomi Anderson, a colored lecturer. She also attended a Campaign Committee meeting in the morning at 564 {E....?] Building to discuss the money question.

entries.fullText:
was at office
all the morning -
Went over to Mrs Harper
for Examiner article this
P.M. at once after lunch -
spent the night
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at the office all morning, went to Mrs. Harper's for an Examiner article in the afternoon, and spent the night.

entries.fullText:
Winifred got off at 9
for a three days
yachting expedition with
10 girls - then Mrs
Harper & self settled
down to the job
at 11.20 I left &
reached 1620 Folsom
just in time for lunch
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's daughter, Winifred, left for a three-day yachting expedition with 10 girls. Susan and Mrs. Harper worked on a job, and Susan left at 11:20 to reach 1620 Folsom just in time for lunch.

entries.fullText:
The Christian Church
Annual Convention
at Garfield Park -
Tabernacle - Santa Cruz -
8 P.M. - Mrs Ella L. Pringle
Miss Hay & self took
8.27 train - reached Santa
Cruz at noon - then went
to Mrs E. G. Green's - & I to
my cousins - Mr & Mrs W.
Pringles - Uncle Elihu
Anthony great Grand
son - the grandson of
Asa - very nice people -
- the audience was large &
most sympathetic - I made a
free & fairly good speech - they
passed a strong resolution
unanimously - took up
collection of only $16 - This
is sum it was but just
half of sum collected
[for?] women's missions with
her after [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends the Christian Church Annual Convention in Santa Cruz, gives a speech, and a resolution is passed.

entries.fullText:
The Suffrage Club
Mrs Everett President
gave us a reception
in their new & beautiful
headquarters - in
Weir Ice Library building
at 10 A.M. - Mrs Mc
Cann - Mrs Green & Mrs
Wilkes spoke - with
Miss Hay & myself
she lunched at the Pope
House - Mrs E.O. Smith
& self at Mrs McCanns
Then we took train
at 1.40 - and reached
San Fran. at 6.30 -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a reception at the Suffrage Club's new headquarters and then travels to San Francisco.

entries.fullText:
was startled this A.M.
by Los Angeles item in
The Call saying the
Southern Suffrage Com
mittees were to organize
themselves as alliances
with the different parties
with whom they sympathized
- wrote a protest -
tried to get Call to put
it in as an Editorial -
but Mr Boyce refused -
so it went in over my
name - & he promised
to send its substance
off by Associated Press -
It will heat the days
if we are to have the[?]
Kilkenny cats played over here
in California - suffrage women
joining the political parties !!!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was startled by a Los Angeles item in The Call saying the Southern Suffrage Committees were to organize themselves as alliances with the different parties with whom they sympathized. She wrote a protest and tried to get Call to put it in as an Editorial but Mr Boyce refused.

entries.fullText:
[Odd Fellows] Hall
Cor of Broadway & 11th Street
Socialist Labor Party - Miss Kellogg
8 P.M. - subject - How
the ballot will lift
women workers so
as to be a help to the
men - instead of
being as now a mill
stone around their necks
Mrs Sargent went over
with me - found a very
small audience - but did
my best - It was very
nearly twelve Oclock when
we reached home -

My article was in the
Call - & all said it was good
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a Socialist Labor Party event at [Odd Fellows] Hall in Oakland with Mrs Sargent. She spoke on the subject of how the ballot will lift women workers so as to be a help to the men - instead of being as now a millstone around their necks. She found a very small audience but did her best. Her article was in the Call and all said it was good.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Sweet came after
breakfast & I dictated
letters until noon - then
had to go to meet the blind
Chris Buckley - the
very chief of what
they call the worst
faction of the S.F.
Democracy - he appeared
very friendly talked smoothly
as any one could - &
promised to influence
his [mate?] to [for?] us
entries.summaryText: Met with Chris Buckley, the chief of a faction of the S.F. Democracy, who promised to influence his mate to help them.

entries.fullText:
Went before the
State Central Com
of the Populist Party -
- they passed resolution
unanimously &
heartily to [?]
our suffrage speeches
on their platforms
Throughout the campaign
Mr Wardall Chair
Mr [Fowles ?] of Fresno
entries.summaryText: Attended a meeting with the State Central Committee of the Populist Party who passed a resolution to support their suffrage speeches on their platforms throughout the campaign.

entries.fullText:
Socialist Baker Party
Meeting at 117 Turk Street
Mrs Sargent - Mrs Sherry
& daughter went with
me - the audience
small - not [?]
They asked how we
expected the ballot
to make women
free - when making
men mere industrial
slaves with it. I
replied by intelligence
& [?] with & for
the people - not with
& for political gains [?]
entries.summaryText: Attended a Socialist Baker Party meeting at 117 Turk Street with Mrs Sargent, Mrs Sherry, and her daughter. Answered questions about how the ballot would make women free.

geographicalLocations: Good Samaritan Mission Episcopalian at 249 2d st - corner of Folsom
entries.fullText:
At Mrs. Sargent's
an officer [?]
this day - in P.M.
wished with Mrs.
Hay to Sen. Sam.
Shortridge - to use
his influence with
[?] to get women
on Republican platform
Spoke this evng at
Good Samaritan Mission
Episcopalian at 249 2d st -
corner of Folsom - the place
was a basement - [?]
but made as clean & nice as
the men could make it -
had about 110 men & women
entries.summaryText: Met with an officer at Mrs. Sargent's and spoke at the Good Samaritan Mission Episcopalian at 249 2d st - corner of Folsom to about 110 men and women.

entries.fullText:
Took 7. Oclock breakfast
& reached Lemon Heights
before Mrs Harper &
Winifred were through
breakfast - Had a
good many interruptions -
the "Boy Orator" - Cornell -
of the Populists - came to
Luncheon - a very earnest
bright young man - Mrs
Baldwin called - working
at Examiner article till
near midnight -
Winifred's young sister spent
evening - & they sat out in garden
until 11. then her mother
sharply commanded her to come
into the house - he is but 22 -
- [[?]]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had breakfast at Lemon Heights with Mrs. Harper and Winifred. She had many interruptions including a visit from the "Boy Orator" Cornell of the Populists. Mrs. Baldwin also called. Winifred's young sister spent the evening with them.

entries.fullText:
Left Mrs Harper at
11.20 - went to office
lunched with Hay & Sweet -
had impression of hand
inside - taken - in Lamp black
sent article to Examiner -
went to Mrs Sargents -
tried to [?aff] it apart in
clean ruching a watch pocket
- dressed again - took dinner
was at Ferry for 7 Oclock
Broad Gage - met Mrs Harper
Winifred & Mrs Baldwin & went
to Germania Hall to the
ratification meeting of Bryan &
Watson - [?] the Oakland
Populists - after speaking - Mrs
Baldwin took me to M. [?]
Theater - head Judge Carpenter
& Charlie Shortridge - Judge Barnes
was through with his speech
- no heartfelt enthusiasm
at [?] & no mention
of suffrage amendment at
Republican ratification meet=
overall with Oakland man not [???ing] the news
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had lunch with Hay and Sweet and sent an article to Examiner. She attended a ratification meeting of Bryan and Watson at Germania Hall with Mrs. Harper, Winifred, and Mrs. Baldwin. She also went to M. [?] Theater with Mrs. Baldwin and met Judge Carpenter, Charlie Shortridge, and Judge Barnes. There was no mention of suffrage amendment at the Republican ratification meeting.

entries.fullText:
Left Lemon Heights - Oakland
at 11 Oclock - Mrs Harper
& daughter Winifred & Mrs Lloyd
Baldwin went to hear the
[Wen???] - [Unitarian ?]
found only Mrs Sargent &
son George - & after Lunch
they went driving to Golden
Gate Park - The article
in this A.M. Examiner is
less satisfactory than any
one before -

Did not go to Friendship
Hall - McAlister St. - at 2. P.M. to
see & hear Carrie Filkins Bush
[?] - as I told her - last
night I would try to do & just
42 years ago she travelled with
me in New York in very
first suffrage campaign.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Oakland and Golden Gate Park, reads an unsatisfactory article in the Examiner, and misses a meeting with Carrie Filkins Bush.

entries.fullText:
Went to the
Congregationalist ministers
Monday morning meeting at Parlor
of Grand Hotel - heard
Rev. J. R. McLean give an
address on needs of that
denomination - several
talked 3 minute speeches -
at close - Mrs Cooper
called on me - & I
gave them a word urging
each to [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting of Congregationalist ministers and speaks briefly about the needs of the denomination.

entries.fullText:
Eight years ago to day -
Aug 11. 1888 - brother
D.H. & Sister Anna O's
little Annette died -
in Mackinaw - Mich -
when Sister had taken
the little one out of
the Kansas heat -

This P.M. went
to {...ville] - Oakland
to Alameda Co. Fair -
- no one could be
heard - & I refused
to try to speak &
came back home
to dinner The
Bay Conference of Congre
gational Ministers to-day
talked of [?] Newspaper
& not a word on the
amendment -!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the death of her brother's daughter, her visit to the Alameda Co. Fair, and the Bay Conference of Congregational Ministers.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Sargent & self
attempted to call on
Bishop Rioridan
- 110 Franklin St - but
man said he was
out of town -
A letter from Mrs
Stanton - dated Aug. 7th
came this noon -
her Harriet & Theodore
[are?] coming over in September
& she wants Hattie to
come speak in Cal
during October - only
lack of money will
hinder her getting an
invitation -
[?] 34 District - Repub
lican meeting in Mission Hall
this evening -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about attempting to call on Bishop Rioridan, a letter from Mrs. Stanton, and a Republican meeting in Mission Hall.

entries.fullText:
[Spoke at 24th
Assembly - Republican
Club meeting in
mission this [?] Hall &
- Mrs Sargent went
with me - Miss May
chaperoned us]
Went over to
Vernon Heights to
Mrs Harper to write
Examiner article -
for next Sunday - on
threat on men -
Denied to women -
came back after
dinner
entries.summaryText: Spoke at a Republican Club meeting, visited Mrs. Harper in Vernon Heights to write an article, and returned after dinner.

entries.fullText:
Central State Com. meeting
at 565 - Head Quarters -
with meeting of Presidents' of
Local Clubs of Alameda
County - in forenoon
- Mrs Sargent & self
took 2.42 train for
San Jose - to visit
dear Mrs Goodrich
- her daughter - [Jinnie]
Knox Mattox - found
there Mrs. Kidd - & her
sister Mrs Grafton -
entries.summaryText: Attended a meeting in the morning and then traveled to San Jose to visit Mrs. Goodrich and others.

entries.fullText:
At Mrs Goodrichs
San Jose -
Her grandson
Knox - took me a
[?] & pleasant
drive in the forenoon
- & Mrs Sargent
out in afternoon -
I took a [?]
sleep in P.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends time with Mrs. Goodrich's grandson Knox and Mrs. Sargent in San Jose.

entries.fullText:
In San Jose
Mrs G took Mrs S. &
self to the Cemetery
Oak Hill - where
rest the bodies of
her first & second
husband & her two
grand-daughters -
Louise - & the last
one - Winifred - who
died just a year
ago next - [?] Aug 23rd
& her heart aches over
their break bitterly -as
does that of her mother
Mrs Mattox
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Cemetery Oak Hill in San Jose with Mrs. G to pay respects to her family members who have passed away.

entries.fullText:
Mrs S. & self Left
San Jose - at 9.12 A.M. -
- at evening - I went
to [Menham ?] Hotel
Cor. Mason & Sutter - &
spoke to the Ladies
of the Hotels - hard
work it was - too -
Mrs Long & Miss Hay -
- for the first time I
opened front door with
her latch key -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Mrs. S. left San Jose and went to Menham Hotel. Susan spoke to the ladies of the hotel and opened the front door with Mrs. Long's latch key.

entries.fullText:
Spent all the
forenoon - moving
all of my [?] into
Dr Elizabeths office
next room [?] of
mine - & fixing mine
for Rev Anna Shaw &
her best girl - my niece
[Suzy? or Lucy?] E. Anthony - &
in P.M. went to the
Swifts to a 24th District
Precinct Presidents
meeting - there are 20- some
10 or 12 present - after that
went to Head Quarters
then home to dinner
- & 2.7.15 was in bed
tired enough - & slept
right through to [?] Oclock
next morning
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony moved her things to Dr. Elizabeth's office and fixed her own office for Rev Anna Shaw and her niece. She then went to a meeting at Swifts and later to Head Quarters before going home to sleep.

entries.fullText: Wrote letters to Mrs [Downey?] on death of her husband to Sister Anna of brother Daniels trouble with a fearful carbuncle on back of his neck - to Mrs. C. C. Catt - in Idaho - and at 2.20 - started for 16th St. to meet Lucy E. A. found her train had arrived at 4.10 - so rushed back on same ferry boat - & found her quietly sitting there - along - she had a pleasant though hot trip We talked over herself & all our family
entries.summaryText: Susan wrote letters and met Lucy E. A. to talk about family.

entries.fullText: At 11 A.M. went over to Lemon Heights to write Examiner article with Mrs Ida A. Harper - at evening - went to Army & Navy Republican League Hall & spoke to the old soldiers - one half audience were women - when we reached home - found Winifred with her caller - out in garden 11 Oclock - I slept in [wicks ?] room down stairs - bed & table & everything full of cigar smells fresh & old -
entries.summaryText: Susan wrote an article with Mrs Ida A. Harper and spoke at the Army & Navy Republican League Hall.

entries.fullText:
Returned to 1620 after Lunch -
at evening - spoke in the
Franklin & Lally's Street
Presbyterian Church
- 20 men & 400 women
as usual - the Pastor
Mr Stewart came
home with me - had
never thought why all
church matters unworthy
attention of politicians?
Lucy E., Miss Hay and
George Sargent met Miss
Shaw at 16th St Station
- they were snugly
in bed - when I got back
It is good to have
Anna back again to
do the speaking papers
all sort of facts
meetings
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spoke at the Franklin & Lally's Street Presbyterian Church and met with several people including Miss Shaw at 16th St Station.

entries.fullText:
Central Com - Miss
Hay Chairman - at Head
Quarters - after it Mrs
Swift took Miss Shaw
Lucy E. & self to Lunch
at Woman's Exchange
- after that Mrs Swift
walked with me to
Clay St. - between Kearny & Sansome
- The Call office - Editorial -
- & climbed up the stairs
to urge Mr Boyce to write
an editorial for Sunday Call
- then back to 1630 - after
dinner - Mrs Sargent - Miss Hay
& self - (Lucy E's cold too bad)
met Miss Hay, Mrs Blinn
Mrs [Kerry?] & the last - & went to
Republican. [?] - Eddy & Jane
- Miss [?] made long
speech of 10 minutes & carried
all by storm - everyone pleased
Dr. Elizabeth home from
Blythesdale this P.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a Central Committee meeting and had lunch at the Woman's Exchange. She also visited The Call office and urged Mr. Boyce to write an editorial for Sunday Call. Later, she attended a Republican meeting and heard a long speech by Miss [?].

entries.fullText:
All of us remained
all day -
at home -
Miss Shaw - Lucy & self
Dr. Mrs Sargent & George
and no one called
We lazed & read
& wrote letters &
looked over papers
all day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and her companions spent the day at home, reading, writing letters, and looking over papers.

entries.fullText: At Home - 1620 Folsom -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at home at 1620 Folsom.

entries.fullText: At home 1620 Folsom
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated August 25, 1896, written at home in 1620 Folsom.

entries.fullText:
At Home
at 4.20 P.M. went
with Mrs Swift to
call on her minister
Episcopal - Moreland
- he doesn't see any
principle of justice
in suffrage -
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated August 26, 1896, written at home. Susan B. Anthony went with Mrs. Swift to visit her minister, who didn't see any principle of justice in suffrage.

entries.fullText:
Took the 10.40 train
to Menlo Park - to Luncheon
with Mrs Leland Stanford
Mrs Jane Lathrop Stanford
- a hyoung man Hall - &
his mother Mrs Kellogg - went
on same train & had the coach
man stop & take them in -
they were Divine Healers - & the
errand was to get $200. of Mrs
Stanford to transport them
back to New York - most
bossy demand - her son must
be saved from suicide!!
Mrs Stanford was very firm in
her refusal - & yet invited
them to stay & lunch - they in a
measure spoiled my day -
Still Mrs S. was very earnest in
her interest in the am't - her
[?] Miss Stanford - & sister in law
Mrs C. Lathrop were [?] - I
returned on the 5.20 train
Miss Shaw spoke
this evening at Martinez
[Suzy ? or Lucy?] went with her
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had lunch with Mrs. Leland Stanford and Mrs. Jane Lathrop Stanford in Menlo Park. They were joined by a young man named Hall and his mother, Mrs. Kellogg, who were Divine Healers. They demanded $200 from Mrs. Stanford to transport them back to New York, claiming that her son must be saved from suicide. Mrs. Stanford refused but invited them to stay for lunch. Susan B. Anthony returned on the 5.20 train. Miss Shaw spoke in the evening at Martinez and was accompanied by Suzy or Lucy.

entries.fullText:
Took the 8.27 train
for Watsonville - where
I was the guest of Mr &
Mrs Tuttle - and spoke
at the Santa Cruz County
Populist Convention
in the evening - Mrs
Green there with me -
- Mr Drew - a
farmer 8 miles out
was the chairman - It
is a sad spectacle
to see the honest
earnest farmers so
credulous that free silver
will bring them plant -
Miss Shaw spoke for
Simpson M.E. Church -
& after it was taken
to Presidio Heights &
spoke to that Repub. Club
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony took the 8.27 train to Watsonville, where she was the guest of Mr. and Mrs. Tuttle. She spoke at the Santa Cruz County Populist Convention in the evening, accompanied by Mrs. Green. Mr. Drew, a farmer 8 miles out, was the chairman. Miss Shaw spoke for Simpson M.E. Church and later spoke to the Republican Club at Presidio Heights.

entries.fullText:
At 1620 Folsom
Had a business
meeting - Miss Shaw
spoke at Union
League Republican
Club - Lucy E. went
with her - also
Mrs Sargent
entries.summaryText: Business meeting and Miss Shaw spoke at Union League Republican Club with Lucy E. and Mrs Sargent.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw & Lucy E. both
with us at 1630 - all of us
patched or darned all day -
after dinner I took cars to
Mrs Blum's - but no one was in -
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw and Lucy E. spent the day with us patching and after dinner Susan went to Mrs Blum's but no one was in.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw left for
San Diego - at 9 Oclock
Lucy E. went across
Ferry with her -
I spent the day
at home 1620 Folsom
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw left for San Diego and Lucy E. went with her. Susan B. Anthony spent the day at home.

entries.fullText:
2nd Ward - Oakland
Republican Club 8 P.M.
Alameda County
annual meeting at
Suffrage Club
Lunched & spoke at
Ebel Club at 12. noon -
a 2. went into the
County Con - where they had
a closely drawn battle
for President - superseding
Mrs Stocker - with Mrs
Lloyd Baldwin - It
remains to be seen whether
the work will be bettered
by the change - the Stocker
regime had checkmated
any move & wish of the State
was there till perhaps 6 - then
dined with Mrs Harper & went
to Enterprize Hall - Mrs
Fisher Clarence of the club
Miss Mollie Connor's We
got home at - 11 - [?]
with [???] Mrs. Harper
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended several meetings and events in Oakland, including the Alameda County annual meeting at the Suffrage Club and a closely drawn battle for President at the County Con. She also lunched and spoke at the Ebel Club and dined with Mrs. Harper before going to Enterprize Hall.

entries.fullText:
met at Beethoven Hall
336 - Post Street
Ms Sargent with me - carriage sent
for us - Mrs Haight of Berkley one
of the leaders - only 40 -
women present - the
President said I made the
most convincing speech she had
heard - but still she was not
altogether persuaded.
Letter from Sister Mary
saying she had received Mrs.
Shaw & my letter saying we
would be in Rochester Nov. 14 -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting at Laurel Hall Club in San Francisco and receives a letter from Sister Mary.

entries.fullText:
Republican meeting - at 2:20 PM
Took luncheon with dear
Mrs Goodrich - who gave
me 50 dollars in gold for the
State Com. - Col. Morehouse
presided - Hale's Hall
packed at least 1,000
more that half women
and right under the roof
hotter than need be
made a half-hour speech
and a man cleared the
way - so that I rushed
through the crowd &
got to station in time for
5 P.M. train - the driver
rushed me through & he
rushed back to the hall
for Mrs Goodrich - at
Menlo Park - Miss Stanford
seeing me in the car - said
Aunt Jane is in her carriage
& would be glad to see her
so rushed out & she told
me the W.R. passes would
come thru -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a Republican meeting in San Jose and has lunch with Mrs. Goodrich who donates $50 in gold for the State Com.

entries.fullText: McGuire Club - 8 P.M.
entries.summaryText: Attended McGuire Club meeting at 8 P.M.

entries.fullText: Ukiah - Mendocino - County Democratic Party Campaign - Opening - Stopped with dear Mrs Nichols' son O. Carpenter & daughter Mrs Carpenter Hudson
entries.summaryText: Attended the opening of the County Democratic Party Campaign in Ukiah and stayed with Mrs. Nichols' family.

entries.fullText: Wea. TUES. SEPT. 8, 1896 Ther.

Methodist Episcopal state
Conference at Pacific Grove
Passed a splendid resolution
Leona Heights [?][?]
Mrs Babcock Lake Hanson
Grange 10 A.M. Alameda -
Park Hotel - had a
fair audience - spoke
from a music stand -
Anna Shaw then too -
also Rev J.R. McLean
who introduced - Mrs Babcock
seemed very happy -
entries.summaryText: Attended the Methodist Episcopal state Conference in Pacific Grove and spoke at the Grange in Alameda with Anna Shaw and Rev J.R. McLean. Mrs Babcock was also present and seemed happy.

entries.fullText: Wea. THUR. SEPT. 10, 1896 Ther.

Pacific Coast Association
Native Sons of Vermont
Odd Fellows Hall -
- met Mrs Blinn there
very unsatisfactory -the
people there for
a dance - & good time
to learn or listen -
President F. Dillingham
- the Blinns brought &
gave me to bring
home the largest
bunch of grapes
muscats I ever saw
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting at the Odd Fellows Hall and meets Mrs. Blinn. She finds the event unsatisfactory and notes that the people were there for a dance and good time. She also mentions meeting President F. Dillingham and receiving a large bunch of grapes from the Blinns.

entries.fullText:
Nevada City - guest
Mrs Crawfords - I
- spoke in McKinly
Club meeting - in Opera
House - no Armory
Hall - Left San Fran
at 7 A.M. freight off
the track - so that didn't
reach N. City till near
7 P.M. - Mrs C. had had
supper waiting two hours -
so took a light bit & a
cup of coffee - stripped
off & went into bed - &
when Mrs. C. called me
at 8.20 - she had to
[??ff] three times -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Nevada City as a guest of Mrs. Crawfords. She spoke at a McKinly Club meeting in the Opera House since the Armory Hall was not available. She arrived late due to a freight delay and had a light meal before going to bed.

entries.fullText: Wea. SUN. SEPT. 20, 1896 Ther.
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated September 20, 1896.

entries.fullText:
Wea. MON. SEPT. 21, 1896 Ther.
At home -at
Mrs Sargents -
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated September 21, 1896, mentioning being at home and at Mrs. Sargent's.

entries.fullText:
Tooke the 4.15 boat
to Oakland - to
Mrs Lloyd Baldwins -
Vernon Heights - went
to bed - got a short sleep -
- threatened rain -
some dozen women
& two men came
to her parlors - &
talked precinct
work - & ways & means
- I was in honest
trim for talk -
simply could not -
so set the rest
at it - Mrs Eliza
[Jaffer ?] Wilkes was there
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes to Oakland and meets with a group of women and two men to discuss precinct work and ways and means.

entries.fullText:
Left Oakland on
7 A.M. train for
Sacramento -
found Mrs J. F. Swift
on train - & on reaching
some point - Mrs C. B.
came on board - she had
come from Calistoga -
we went to Golden Eagle
Mrs E. G. Green at station -
- Had a good audience
in the Opera House -
Mr [Bruner ?] - Chair - [?]
Repub County Com. president
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Sacramento and speaks at the Opera House to a good audience.

entries.fullText:
Left Sacramento at 10.30
dined on [?] stuff at
Lathrop & reached
Madera - at 4.20 -
two women grabbed me
& pulled in opposite ways each
saying she was to entertain
me - I finally told them that
Mrs. C. would go with one &
I with other - Mine was Mrs. M. James
[???ent] - a niece of Sarah Knox Goodrich]
- Mrs [?] with her - a lady -
- both women declared herself the
manager - but Mrs [????ent]
had hired the hall - invited
leading men & women to platform
& rushed to the front &
presided - well it was
a sad muddle - & neither
party can do very much
unless both surrender
boss-ship to a third party
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony describes her journey from Sacramento to Madera and the confusion caused by two women who both wanted to entertain her.

entries.fullText:
Visalia - Tulare Co. -
guests of Mrs Johnson -
left Madera at 4.20 - &
reached Visalia at 8.45 -
were rushed to Mrs J's
she actually split the kindling
wood - made the fire, boiled the
water & made coffee for us -
- they had music so her
crowd waited the more
patiently - it was a splendid one - the
women here are splendid
- they had 10 cts admission
and took $84.50 -
sent it all to her state
society Mrs Spery -
- Mrs J. insisted we
should stay to dinner - [to?]
- we consented - but my coffee
or something else kept me awake
so I never slept a wink
to my knowledge - heard the 6.10
train move off - &c -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Visalia and describes the hospitality of Mrs. Johnson and the success of the event, which raised $84.50 for the state society of Mrs. Spery.

entries.fullText:
Left Mrs Johnsons - Visalia
at 2 P.M. by carriage & reached
Hanford 21 miles at
5.30 - through sand &
dust & heat - well tired
was no name for us -
- both stripped off & went
to bed for a half-hour -
Mrs L.A. Popkins our
Hostess - had Mr Carr & his
wife Rev Sarah Pratt [Car?]
of LaMore - & sundry
others to dinner - she had
expected us on the 8 A.M.
train - & had got 10 invited to
a noon dinner - who were now
at a cold meat supper - with
a good cup of coffee - [ham?]
- it was a pen built against
a brick wall building - with
fence 20 feet high on the other
three sides - the moon shining over
all - a magnificent audience
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived at Hanford, tired and dusty, after a long carriage ride from Visalia. She stayed with Mrs. L.A. Popkins and attended a dinner with Mr. Carr, his wife Rev Sarah Pratt, and others.

entries.fullText:
Left Hanford on 6.20
A.M. train - dear Mrs
Dopkins getting up at 5 -
getting a nice breakfast
- steak &c - with wheat in
much cream lots of it and
peaches & coffee - It was
a fearfully hot & dusty
day until after passing
Lathrop - reached
San Fran at 4.45 -
dreadfully tired - but
glad of the cool - almost
cold breath of air - Mrs
Catt went to California Hotel
& after dinner came with Miss Hay
to talk - Mrs Swift also -
- Mrs Blinn called before
dinner - full of life & hope
though very hoarse & off [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Hanford and arrived in San Francisco, where she met with Mrs. Catt, Miss Hay, Mrs. Swift, and Mrs. Blinn. She was glad to escape the hot and dusty weather.

entries.fullText: - At Mrs Sargents - 1620 Folsom St. - Mrs C.C. left on 7. train for Woodland - Miss Shaw & Lucy E. here - go to Alameda in P.M. -- I wrote letters all the morning - after Lunch went to Head Quarters & talked over work with Miss Hay - gave interview to the Call & Chronicle Reporters - got letter from little Dr Mary C Hussey East Orange - N.J. - telling of her thought to study Law - [?] of her M.D. so that she can & could help poor women.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her day at Mrs. Sargent's, where she wrote letters, went to headquarters, gave interviews, and received a letter from Dr. Mary C Hussey.

entries.fullText: speak in East Oakland at Mrs Alice R. Wellman's - 1315 East 14th Street - take narrow gauge & Hayward Car to house - Mrs Kate Tupper Galpin spoke here - also Mrs Sarah M. Severance - Mrs G. altogether the better - J. R McLean to dinner at Mrs Wellman's - she is a widow with two daughters at home - Spent the night there - Mrs Baldwin presented & a club formed - with Mrs Hush Pres - & Miss Wellman vice Pres.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks in East Oakland at Mrs. Alice R. Wellman's and spends the night there. A club is formed with Mrs. Hush as President and Miss Wellman as Vice President.

entries.fullText:
Lunch at noon at Dr
Alice Bush - the daughter
of Davide & Ellen Morgan
Bush - & granddaughter
of Abigail Bush - Mrs
Sargent & Mrs Sweet there
& an older sister of Dr
Alice's -

Left at 2.30 - & went
to Sausalito - & spoke
in a Pooling room -
well cleaned it &
decorated - was the
guest of the [?]
of a Cong. minister - Mrs -

Mrs Bell - got up the meeting.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had lunch with Dr. Alice Bush and others before going to Sausalito to speak at a meeting organized by Mrs. Bell.

entries.fullText:
Meeting at Mrs Friends
222 - Eleventh Street -
guest of Mr & Mrs
Frederick Stratton -
dined & spent night -
Mr S. running for State
senator - so reserved
in public - wife very
intelligent -
Mrs Vrooman - Mrs Steele
& Mrs Harper made
remarks at the meeting
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a meeting at Mrs. Friends and stayed with Mr. and Mrs. Frederick Stratton. Mrs. Vrooman, Mrs. Steele, and Mrs. Harper made remarks at the meeting.

entries.fullText:
Left Mrs F. Strattans
on the 8.45 train for
San Fran -

I spoke this night
in the auditorium -
Republican [?] - cor
of Eddy & Mason streets - with
Congressman Loud before me
& Pal Morehouse of San
Jose after - the latter
was splendid - so was
the nominee Taylor - for
mayor - in good words
for amendment - &
Miss Hay - & all said
[?] a good speech
- I believe such a 10
minutes speech in a party
meeting makes more con
verts - then a whole
two hours of speeches in
a specially called W. S. meeting
The Strattans came with
1901 - Harrison Street -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spoke at an auditorium in San Francisco with Congressman Loud and Pal Morehouse before and after her respectively. She also spoke in good words for amendment and Miss Hay. She believes that a 10-minute speech in a party meeting makes more converts than a whole two hours of speeches in a specially called W. S. meeting.

entries.fullText:
Took 9. train for
Martinez [underlined] - the old
home of Abigail Bush
Mrs Frances W. Fish
met me - took me a drive
to see the old Bush farm -
- then back to dinner &
a good afternoon sleep
- Mr John Swett presided &
it was a splendid audience
Mrs North President
& Mrs Julia Fish -stayed
at Mrs Fish's all night -
- every sort of fruit &
nut in their lovely
garden
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited Martinez, the old home of Abigail Bush, and was taken on a drive to see the old Bush farm. She stayed at Mrs. Fish's house and enjoyed a good afternoon sleep. She also had dinner with Mr. John Swett and a splendid audience. She stayed overnight with Mrs. North and Mrs. Julia Fish and enjoyed every sort of fruit and nut in their lovely garden.

entries.fullText:
Left Martinez at 9.45 - &
reached San Rafael at 12.20
- found the Grand son of
dear Mrs C.J. H. Nichols
at his home - Lewis Grant
Carpenter - & his brother
Frank L. Carpenter - then
George Nichols - the holy son
of dear Mr. Nichols - daughter
& Nellie C.
Nichols - whom I saw married
with Charles Carter -
her sister - Miss Kate
Howard Nichols
who had come down from
Potter valley to see his sister
Nellie married - both are
very sweet - unaffected girls
- & show their mothers
[?] blood - Mr
Carters friend & employer - Mr
George Hinkman -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits San Rafael and meets with the family of Mrs. C.J. H. Nichols, including Lewis Grant Carpenter, Frank L. Carpenter, George Nichols, Nellie C. Nichols, Charles Carter, Miss Kate Howard Nichols, and Mr. George Hinkman.

entries.fullText: [No entry for this date]
entries.summaryText: No entry for this date.

entries.fullText:
California State Grange
Sacramento - annual meeting
Master State Grange
W. W. Green - Sacramento
[?] - Don Mills - Santa Rosa
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended the annual meeting of the California State Grange in Sacramento where she met with the Master State Grange, W. W. Green from Sacramento, and [?] from Don Mills in Santa Rosa.

entries.fullText:
Benecia - [?]
Mrs - Mellin
Mrs J. G. Johnson
Mrs Ida Billings
meeting in Congregational
Church -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a meeting in Congregational Church in Benecia with Mrs Mellin, Mrs J. G. Johnson, and Mrs Ida Billings.

entries.fullText:
Protrerro Opera House
with Mrs Eliza Tupper
Wilkes - came in
from Benecia - on
the 8 - train -
Mrs Sargent with
me to [?] to be large
audiences of work
men - but - alas
not - 30 were present=
dear Mrs Angelo &
others worked hard
[?] 2,00 [hits ?] &
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Protrerro Opera House with Mrs Eliza Tupper and Mrs Sargent, and the disappointment of a small audience of workmen despite the hard work of Mrs Angelo and others.

entries.fullText:
Central Com. meeting in
forenoon - at 2.15 - took
narrow gauge - found
Mrs A. A. Moore at
station - with her cousin
& horses - for Mrs. Baldwin
& self to call on the
Smith - (Borax) at her
artistic home in E. Oakland
to beg money - got the
promise - saw her in
old New England kitchen
out in the grounds
with 20 boys & girls club -
got back at 6.20 for
dinner & rest - to bed
very soon after -
entries.summaryText: Attended a Central Com. meeting and visited the Smith in E. Oakland to beg for money.

entries.fullText:
At home all day
cleaning up my file
of letters & wrote
- white [?]
Lucy C. is suffering
on her bed - on [?]
twelfth [underlined] day - for this
month's time -
entries.summaryText: Stayed at home and tended to personal matters, including caring for Lucy C. who is ill.

entries.fullText:
Left San Fran at 8.27 -
reached San Luis Obispo
at 5.15 - had a hot dusty
nine hours on the train
through Salinas Valley
Mrs. B. J. Whitmer
met me - & I was her
guest - a good husband
& two lovely grown up
daughters - Kate &
Carrie -
Mrs T.T. [Crittenden?] Pres.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from San Francisco to San Luis Obispo, meeting with Mrs. B. J. Whitmer and her family.

entries.fullText:
Left San Luis Obispo at
5.30 P.M. to speak
ten minutes from tail end
of the train arrv Grange
Santa Maria & Ni Pomo
then sleep at Los Olinas -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left San Luis Obispo and spoke for ten minutes from the tail end of the train at Grange Santa Maria and Ni Pomo before sleeping at Los Olinas.

entries.fullText: Wea. SUN. NOV. 1, 1896 ther.

Last Grand rally - [in Metropolitan Temple
before our fate is decided!]
On race track
in Oakland - Thomas
B. Reed - of Maine - the speaker
15 or 20,000 people - Mrs
Shaw spoke following him
- & at close of her talk
her audience called for
Mrs Anthony & said
vote for Amt. No. 6 - The
first thing - & they shouted
[?] - we will!!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a rally in Metropolitan Temple and a race track event in Oakland where Thomas B. Reed speaks and Mrs. Shaw and Mrs. Anthony are called upon to speak. The audience calls for Mrs. Anthony to vote for Amt. No. 6.

entries.fullText:
Election Day -
Wm. McKinley - Republican nominee
Palmer of Ill. Democratic "
Bryan of Neb - Dem. Pop. "
California & Idaho
woman suffrage amendments to
be voted
entries.summaryText: Summary: Election Day with the Republican nominee Wm. McKinley, Democratic nominee Palmer of Ill., and Dem. Pop. nominee Bryan of Neb. California & Idaho voting on woman suffrage amendments.
Summary: No entry written on this day.

entries.fullText:
[Grand Rally - Oakland ]
State annual meeting -
Golden Gate - hall -
entries.summaryText: Attended State annual meeting in Oakland at Golden Gate hall.

entries.fullText:
Grand Rally - San Francisco -
Jubilee ?
entries.summaryText: Attended Grand Rally in San Francisco, possibly a Jubilee event.

entries.fullText:
Leave San Francisco at 6 P.M.
for home - after an absence of
over eight months -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves San Francisco after an absence of over eight months.

entries.fullText:
Stop at Reno - Nevada -
for a Sunday P.M. or
evening meeting -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stops at Reno, Nevada for a Sunday meeting.

entries.fullText: [Kansas City - Missouri]
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on November 11, 1896 from Kansas City - Missouri.

entries.fullText:
Kansas City - Missouri
guest - Mrs Sarah Coates
Cor. 10th and Penn street
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on November 12, 1896 from Kansas City - Missouri with guest Mrs Sarah Coates and location at Cor. 10th and Penn street.

entries.fullText:
Political Equality Club Banquet
in Rochester - & S.B.A. must
be home in time for it - sure -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the Political Equality Club Banquet in Rochester and mentions that she must be home in time for it.

entries.fullText:
Left Bensonhurst at
3 P.M. had reached
Fall River Boat at
6 Oclock - Rachel with me - it was my first
Sound trip since 30
years ago - pleasant
but cold - [She ?] got into
berth with me & talked until
almost morning - While
the great machinery paddled
us along - R. is a wonder
fully strong woman in many
directions - If only one hadn't
put that censure of Mrs Stanton's
Bible into her last years report
as Con. Sec!! - I should say
in all directions, but that
was caused either by a
weak or wicked spirit -
I cannot divine which - even
at this distance -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Bensonhurst and traveled to Fall River Boat with Rachel. They talked until almost morning. Susan mentions Mrs Stanton's Bible and a weak or wicked spirit.

entries.fullText:
Wm L. & Ellen W. Garrison
1763 - Beacon Street
Brookline Mss -
Rachel Father [?] & I reached
the Hotel [?] - Boston
& there found - the first [?]
Mrs Emma Shafter Howard
of Oakland - Mrs Charles [?]
Howard the fashionables all here -
- after breakfast - I went to her
room & talked & rested & lunched
until 2 P.M. then went into
Council Ex. Com. meeting in
parlor - Miss Shaw with every
[?] of officers present - at
5.30 - Miss Shaw & self went
out to the Garrisons - William
was going off to speak that evening -
so we visited with dear
Ellen & Agnes all the evening -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony met with various people in Boston, including Emma Shafter Howard and Miss Shaw. She also visited with Ellen and Agnes Garrison in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Ex Com - Public Meeting
Young Mens Christian Ass'n
Hall - at 9.50 - not
over 200 gathered [at]
during the whole morning -
- Lunched with dear Mrs
Garrison -reception at
Mrs Bonds - Commonwealth
Avenue from 4 to 6 - after it
went with Mrs Howard
to dinner at the Vendome
then a Business meeting in
evening - and back to
Garrisons to sleep
Mrs. Dickman does
splendidly & Mrs Robbins
vastly better than I had
expected -
entries.summaryText: Attended a public meeting and had lunch and dinner with friends. Attended a business meeting in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Morning session of the
Council - did not go -
neither did Miss Shaw
but at 3 went to the Vendome
to Business meeting - and
from 4 to 6 - a reception in
the parlors - large numbers
called - dined with
dear Mrs Howard - then
went to Y.M.C.A. Hall
& found a full house -
that seemed quite alive
in spirit - May W. Sewall
dressed in white mightily
conspicuous - William &
Ellen attended & we all
went home together -
I do not feel any more
hope of great success of
the [C???] combination - but
hope it will grow -
entries.summaryText: Attended a business meeting and a reception. Had dinner with a friend and attended a full house event at Y.M.C.A. Hall.

entries.fullText:
Left the Garrisons - with
Ella as Escort to
catch the 2 P.M. train
for Concord N. Hampshire -
but were just a minute
late - saw the train
moving out of station -
so she waited & we visited
until 5 Oclock - sending
a telegram to Mrs Pillsbury
arrived at Concord
at 7 - Helen P. Coggswell
met me - we walked to
their home & home of Parker
and Mrs Sarah -----
Pillsbury - he 87- and
she 74 - He is very
feeble & changed - from
stroke of paralysis a year
ago last June - the [family ?]
friend & late husband of Helen
died a year ago - Braniard
Coggswell -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Concord, New Hampshire and meets with various people.

entries.fullText:
In Concord N.H.
at 10 A.M. Helen es-
corted me to Mrs [?] Smith
Whites - husband was Nathanial
White - & visited with her
79 years old - feeble from
rheumatism till church
was out - then went
home with Helen - then
dine on roast chicken at
3 P.M. - & we talked &
talked - I visited P. [G. I. ?]
study room up stairs in
which Helen keeps a coal
stone fire - so it is always
warm for him - at 7
I went again to Mrs White's &
after the Church - taking
a cup of chocolate with her
& her daughter Mrs -
then back & early to bed
[I ?] found their Unitarian
minister, like the Rev & Mrs
Frank L. Phalen
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends time with Helen and visits Mrs. Smith Whites in Concord, New Hampshire.

entries.fullText:
Left Concord at 10 A.M.
reached Boston - called
at W.S. Office - H.B.D.
escorted me to Register
office where I lunched
Isabel [?], daughter
and Alice Stone Black-
well - after that went
to Brookline to the
Garrisons - again
William had to out
to lecture at Woburn
or somewhere - but
had pleasant evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Boston, Concord, and Brookline, and spends time with various people.

entries.fullText:
[Following crossed out: Left Boston on 10.45 A.M.
train for Pautucket - then
met John Lyman husband
of Lillie Chase Lyman and
drove over to Valley Falls
to the house & home of
our dear Elizabeth Buffum
Chace - she was 90 years old]
Oh, no, at 12.10 -
Ellen & I took train for
West Medford to Lunch
with Lucretia Motts daughter
& Edward M. Davis wife
Maria Mott Davis - living
with her daughter Anna
Davis Hallowell -
- we returned on 2.30 train
visited Harvard College grounds
- Mrs Davis is over 80 -
William was home - & we talked
of the olden days all the
evening - this was my last
night with them - I love both dearly -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits West Medford and has lunch with Lucretia Mott's daughter and Edward M. Davis's wife, Maria Mott Davis. She also visits Harvard College grounds and spends time with William.

entries.fullText: Now - Left Boston at 10.45 ay Pawtucket - John Lyman drove me over to Valley Falls - the house & home of Ms Elizabeth [[Buffrim?]] [?] who was 90 years old this very day - very feeble - still sent for me to go to her at once - after lunch I went again - & at leaving at 4.30 - yet again - Anna then arrived at 4 Oclock - travelling since 10. with dinner - & no one thought to ask her - Mrs Lillie Chase Lyman her daughter was lovely - her daughter Mary Chase - came & had the cake & 90 little candles need to be lighted - Mrs Chase sent both of us to Providence in her carriage -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Ms Elizabeth on her 90th birthday in Valley Falls and then travels to Providence with Mrs. Chase.

entries.fullText: In Providence at Mrs Amy Eddy Harris - & Miss Sarah J. Eddys - in the old mansion of James Eddy - the husband of Eliza Jackson Eddy - who took the two daughters off to Europe when they were little children - to the heartbreak of the dear mother - it was this act that moved Francis Jackson to place $5.000 in Wendell Phillips hands for suffrage work - & in turn caused Mrs Eddy to will the residing of her estate to to Lucy Shaw & me $24.000 each - Sarah had just taken a little house outside the [] grounds to live quietly & alone -- so we were really the guests of Dr & Mrs Harris with their two little baby boys
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mrs. Amy Eddy Harris and Miss Sarah J. Eddys in Providence and learns about the history of the Eddy family and their connection to the suffrage movement.

entries.fullText:
In Providence
acting President - Mrs
Ellen M. Bolles -
called with a $25. check
for Miss Shaw & me - cash
from dear Mrs Chace
Miss Shaw & I called
on Mrs Anna Garlin
Spencer - who is the
Pastor of the Chapel
built and endowed with
a $100,000 - by Mr Eddy -
in yard with the House
- In P.M. while
Anna went to the meeting
spoke & took the 4
P.M. train for Johnstown Pa.
I slept & rested - in the
evening I went to Church &
spoke - fair audience -
but California's enthusiastic
audiences have spoiled me
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is in Providence and meets with Mrs Ellen M. Bolles and Mrs Anna Garlin Spencer. She also speaks at a church in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Left Providence in the
10 A.M. Limited train -
reached New York 2 Oclock
left [basket?] at depot -
called on Mrs Stanton -
& Harriet - got back
to cousin Semantha's
by 6.20 - slept there
she furnishing night dress -
after playing cards -
desperation - with
cousin S. cousin Carrie
Vail Ladd & Miss Powell
the friend , "companion",
cousin S. calls her - it
made a busy day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Providence and travels to New York where she visits Mrs Stanton and stays with cousin Semantha. She spends the evening playing cards with family and friends.

entries.fullText:
At Home
in forenoon called at
Mrs Matilda Burtis Sagans -
- when Matilda Anthony
Mosher died Saturday A.M. -
then at Dr Porter Fowles
when Marie Porter died at
midnight. Saturday night -
then to see Sarah Willis
& Mary Hallowell -
both far from well -
the friends to seem to
be slipping over the
big river so rapidly -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about visiting friends and acquaintances, including Matilda Anthony Mosher and Marie Porter, who passed away.

entries.fullText:
At Home - 17 Madison St.
Niece Maggie McLean Baker &
her little boy Lawrence - six
years old - arrived at 11 A.M.
from Newark -
In P.M. at 2. Maggie
sister Mary & self went
to the [funeral of Mrs Maria J. Porter, in the ] old home of Sam'l
D. Porter - 67. South Fitzhugh &
now the home of Dr & Mrs
Porter Farley [and Mary Farley] & that of Aunt
Maria Porter - the last few
years - Our dear friend Maria
was born Oct. 18, 1805 - hence
was 91 years & nearly two months
- when she passed on - at midnight
of Saturday - Dec. 12 - Mr Gannet read
& prayed - in too [?] & indistinct
words to be heard by [but few of] the very few
present - but we all knew they were
most fitting & beautiful - My last
hour with her was on my way to
the train for California on the spring
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends the funeral of Maria J. Porter and spends time with family.

entries.fullText:
At home
Niece Maggie & little L -
went to Luncheon with
Minnie Sackett Smith -
Spent forenoon reading
all about Poor Cuba
& the heroic Antonio Maceo's
death - it seems unbe
lievable - that he could
have dared to trust any
Spanish promise - & so
suffered himself to be lured
into the trap - as they say -
Mrs Greenleaf called -
sister Mary went down
town - The Call [underlined] brings
news only to Dec. 10 - it will
be two days yet before it will
bring account of dear Mrs. Cooper
& [Daniel's ?] sad ending -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about spending time with her niece and reading about Cuba and Antonio Maceo's death. She also mentions visitors and waiting for news about Mrs. Cooper and Daniel.

entries.fullText:
At Home
Niece Maggie & little
Lawrence spent the day
with us
Minnie Sackett Smiths &
[her ?] mother came to dinner
with us to day - then went to [?]
so we had a little
chat - after the little
fellow was asleep -
he monopolizes every
minute of his mother
all the day long - he
is a nice child but
not taught to amuse
himself -
No Call [double underlined] came to
day - and it dawned
on me that it was stopped
by my order sent Mr Hutridge
to do so - before I went to
Boston
[Note: there is a line written vertically on the left margin that is not legible]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about spending time with her niece and her niece's child. She also mentions stopping the delivery of a newspaper and sending someone to do so before going to Boston.

entries.fullText:
At HOme - P.E. Club's
Sociable at Mr & Mrs Gannetts
this evening - Sister Mary & self
invited there to tea - with
Mrs Montgomery & Mr & Mrs Grant -
a nice gathering -
Maggie & little Lawrence
chose to spend evening & night
with her friends the Goulds on
[?] street - No Call
came to day - The waiting
to get particulars of
death of Mrs Cooper
& Hattie becomes a
weary one - Can
think of little else
entries.summaryText: Sociable at Mr & Mrs Gannetts with Sister Mary, Mrs Montgomery & Mr & Mrs Grant. Maggie & little Lawrence spent evening with friends. Waiting for news of Mrs Cooper & Hattie.

entries.fullText:
At home
Maggie came back to dinner
- made sundry purchases -
spent evening writing letters to Mary
& [Grandma ?] & Hattie Baker - and
at 9.20 - Sister Mary went
with them to station to
see them off for their Cal-
San Diego home at 10.30 -
the steps were icy & snowy
& the little fellow was
frightened - with his first
feeling of slipperiness - it was
too funny !!
It seemed
hard to have Maggie go
away so far again - & Sad
for her to leave her boy & girl
housekeeping alone in N. Y. flat -
but - such is life - [?]
families to be apart from
part or all -
Thought this A.M. to go
to Reading Room - Arcade to see
if there were any San Francisco
Papers there - found Examiner -
entries.summaryText: Maggie leaves for San Diego. Sister Mary sees them off. Anthony writes letters and goes to the Reading Room.

entries.fullText:
At home - A
Lonesome feeling
all day - from dear
niece Maggie's leaving
on her far away trip
- went again
to Reynolds Reading
Room - Arcade - to
see San Francisco
Examiner - & read
account of the
death of dear Mrs
Cooper & her darling Harriet
- - It is too terrible
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about feeling lonesome at home due to her niece Maggie leaving on a trip. She also mentions reading about the death of Mrs. Cooper and Harriet in the San Francisco Examiner.

entries.fullText:
At Home - Sister Mary
and self went to church
Mr Gannet gave Christ sermon
- then called at Greenleafs -
then dined at Charlotte
Wilbur Griffin's - Mrs Frances
Wilbur Hartwell [- 77 on Feb. 14 1899] - the sister
of dear Julia A. Wilbur
who passed on last spring -
is now living with Charlotte
very feeble - but very bright
& interesting - after this
we called on Mrs Laura
Ramsdell - 80 - feeble
but bright - then
went to tea & evening
at Charles & Mrs Fitch's -
- had talk of how to
celebrate 50th anniversary of
of 1848 Convention - Mrs. F.
says by a pageant - showing
Evolution of women on
all lines - or in this
city in June or Oct. 1898,
in Lyceum Theatre -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about attending church and visiting various people, including Mrs. Frances Wilbur Hartwell, the sister of Julia A. Wilbur who passed away the previous spring. She also discusses plans for celebrating the 50th anniversary of the 1848 Convention, including the possibility of a pageant at the Lyceum Theatre.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Sweet came &
took 5 letters - it
seemed good to
get rid of scribbling
again - in eve'g
wrote with her a long
letter to dear Mrs
Sweet -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Sweet came and took 5 letters. Wrote a long letter to Mrs Sweet.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Sweet came again
- got off letters again
wrote Mrs Lovell White -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Sweet came again and got off letters. Wrote to Mrs Lovell White.

entries.fullText:
Niagara Falls - 527
Jefferson Avenue - to
visit Sarah Anthony
Burtis - daughter of
Saratoga County cousin
Daniel Anthony - she
lives with her daughter
Matilda Burtis Dickenson
- took Mrs Sweet with her
- but Sarah didn't recall
much of her two winters
teaching in our house - at
Battenville N.Y - 1835 & 1836 -
- some 8 or 10 inches of
snow - Sarah was bright
but very feeble - the daughter
Matilda Burtis Dickenson - a
very bright woman of 50 - Sarah
was 88 last month - Dec 14 -
so she looks only two months of
being 10 years older than I,
- had a nice visit - got a
down comforter for Sister Mary's Christmas
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Sarah Anthony Burtis, daughter of her Saratoga County cousin Daniel Anthony, in Niagara Falls. They discuss Sarah's time teaching in Battenville, NY in 1835 and 1836. Susan also visits Matilda Burtis Dickenson, Sarah's daughter, who is a very bright woman of 50. Susan gets a down comforter for Sister Mary's Christmas.

entries.fullText:
At Home -
Letters from Rachel
Mrs Upton & nephew
Burt this A.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives letters from Rachel, Mrs Upton, and nephew Burt at home.

entries.fullText:
Christmas -
Sister Mary & self - all
alone - all day - with
only girl Julia Ames.
- Nicely cooked Turkey &
Cranberries -
At evening we
called at Dr Porter Farleys
- the first Christmas they
have had without their
dear 'Aunt Maria'- and
the first evening I ever sat
there without Miss Porter -
in her chair - either knitting
or embroidering - she kept
her hands ever busy -
& after this called on Sarah
Willis - & then on Mary
H Hallowell - where we took
a cup of tea - Mrs & Mary
Will [Street?] & wife - & after
[Jacob ?] {Port ?] & daughter Georgia
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends Christmas day with Sister Mary and Julia Ames. They visit Dr. Porter Farleys, Sarah Willis, and Mary H. Hallowell.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Sweet here -
got off 8 or 10 letters
Sent off the last of
Mrs Southworths $1,000
given over two years ago
to support National Headquarters
- Have this year paid to
national that - and $400 of
the Eliza Claph gift - &
the Head Quarters has used
up the Mrs Doyon bequest -
also - so that next year -
the National will have
nothing - only what the
girls can raise
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives Mrs. Sweet and sends off letters regarding financial support for National Headquarters.

entries.fullText: Went to U. Church
entries.summaryText: Attended church.

entries.fullText: At Home
entries.summaryText: Stayed at home.

entries.fullText: Sister Mary & self celebrated this last day by staying at home - & thinking of the olden years - when we celebrated it as the birth day of Sister Guelma's husband A.M. McLean - this make him 84 years old
entries.summaryText: Sister Mary and Susan B. Anthony celebrate the last day of the year by staying at home and reminiscing about past celebrations, including the birthday of Sister Guelma's husband A.M. McLean who is now 84 years old.

Ex-Governor of Kansas and a Former
Resident of Rochester
The following dispatch was received
from Topeka, Kan., this morning : "Ex-
Gov. George T. Anthony died last night.
He had been ill three weeks. He was
governor of Kansas from 1877 to 1879 and
was appointed superintendent of insurance
by Gov. Morril, which office he held
up to the time of his death."
Mr. Anthony was for a number of
years in the 70's a resident of Rochester,
occupying with his wife and son the old
homestead at the corner of West and Chili
avenues. He was a distant relative of
Misses Mary S. and Susan B. Anthony of
Madison street.
entries.summaryText: Ex-Governor of Kansas and a Former Resident of Rochester, George T. Anthony, died in Topeka, Kan. He was governor of Kansas from 1877 to 1879 and was appointed superintendent of insurance by Gov. Morril, which office he held up to the time of his death. He was a distant relative of Misses Mary S. and Susan B. Anthony of Madison street.

entries.fullText:
Miss Mary Anthony received last evening
a telegram from San Diego, California
stating that her brother-in-law, Aaron
M. McClean was dead. Jan. 18,1986
Mr. McClean lived for many years in
this city, where he was a well-known insurance
agent, doing business in Reynolds
Arcade. While in this city he lived
with the Misses Anthony at the homestead
on Madison Street.
The telegram did not explain the cause
of his death, but it is likely that it was
old age, as he was about 83 years old.
